{"title_page": "G\u00e9rard Gertoux", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the issue is settled -->\n{{AfDM|page=G\u00e9rard Gertoux (3rd nomination)|year=2020|month=March|day=26|substed=yes|origtag=afdx|help=off}}\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox person\n| name = G\u00e9rard Gertoux\n| birth_date =  {{Birth date and age|1955|03|19}}\n| birth_place = Lyon\n| nationality = French\n| education = [[Master of Science]]<br>[[Engineering physics]]\n| alma_mater = [[\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure d'ing\u00e9nieurs \u00e9lectriciens de Grenoble]]<br>[[Lumi\u00e8re University Lyon 2]]<br>[[\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure de Lyon]]\n| occupation = [[Writer]], [[Hebraist]], [[Tetragrammaton|Tetragram]]mist, [[Astronomist]], [[Chronologist]]\n| organization = [[The International Association for Assyriology]]<br>Association Biblique de Recherche d'Anciens Manuscrits\n| notable_works = ''The Name of God Y.eH.oW.aH Which is pronounced as it is Written I_Eh_oU_Ah''\n| movement = [[Jehovah's Witness]]\n| employer = [[French National Centre for Scientific Research]]\n}}\n'''G\u00e9rard Marcel Laurent Gertoux''' (born in 19 March 1955) is a French academic, physical engineer,<ref name=BnF/><ref name=Thomas>{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Thomas|url=https://reachouttrust.org/the-name-of-god/|title=The JW Name of God Documentary-1 Is it Independent?|date=2017-05-24|website=[[Reachout Trust]]|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> [[Hebraist]],<ref name=BnF>{{cite web|title=Notice de personne: G\u00e9rard Gertoux|website=BnF Catalogue g\u00e9n\u00e9ral|url=https://catalogue.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb13548516z|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref name=LC/><ref name=NLI/> Tetragrammist,<ref name=BnF/><ref name=LC/><ref name=NLI/> Bible scholar, [[Assyriology|Assyriologist]], historian and a researcher specializing in ancient [[near eastern archaeology]]. He is also a member of the [[International Association for Assyriology]] (IAA) and founder of ''Association Biblique de Recherche d'Anciens Manuscrits''.\n\n== Life ==\nG\u00e9rard Gertoux was born in 19 March 1955 at Lyon.<ref name=CV/> G\u00e9rard Gertoux is a [[Jehovah's witness]] since 1982.<ref name=Walsh>{{cite letter|author=William C. Walsh|subject=RE: Follow up of Rapporteur's visit to France (18-29 September 2005)|url=http://www.coordiap.com/Document/onu-2010-eng.pdf|recipient=[[Asma Jahangir]]|pp=5-6}}</ref><ref name=OSCEnHRWF/><ref name=themitchellfirm>{{cite web|title=Executive Report. France: Rising Government Restrictions on Religion|website=themitchellfirm.com|date=October 17, 2011|url=http://www.aicongress.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/France-Executive-Summary-October17.2011.pdf}}</ref> G. Gertoux has been president since 1991 of the Association Biblique de Recherche d'Anciens Manuscrits.<ref>{{cite web|title=le Nom de Dieu en question: \u00abLe Seigneur a dit \u00e0 mon Seigneur [sic !]: 'Assieds-toi \u00e0 ma droite, Jusqu'\u00e0 ce que je fasse de tes ennemis ton marchepied\" (Louis Segond, Mt, 22,44)|date=22 June 2007|url=http://actua.unitariennes.over-blog.com/article-10984645.html}}</ref> From 2012 he become a member of the International Association for Assyriology.<ref name=CV/><ref name=iaassyriology/><ref name=ORCID/>\n\n=== Education ===\nHe obtained a diploma [[Engineering physics|Physical Engineering]] at [[\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure d'ing\u00e9nieurs \u00e9lectriciens de Grenoble]] (I.N.P.G.) in 1979.{{sfn|Gee|2004|}}<ref name=BnF/><ref name=CV>{{cite web|url=https://univ-lyon2.academia.edu/GerardGERTOUX/CurriculumVitae|title=Curriculum Vitae|author=Gertoux, G\u00e9rard}}</ref> In 1985, he obtained a CAPES in Physics to become a certified professor.<ref name=BnF/><ref name=LC>{{cite web|website=Library of Congress|title=G\u00e9rard Gertoux|accessdate=March 30, 2020|url=http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n2002090734.html}}</ref><ref name=NLI>{{cite web|title=G\u00e9rard Gertoux|website=National Library of Israel|accessdate=March 30, 2020|url=http://uli.nli.org.il/F/?func=direct&doc_number=000052631&local_base=nlx10}}</ref> From 1992 to 1993, and 2001, he studied [[Hebrew language]] at Acad\u00e9mie des langues anciennes with Elie Cohen, at Sessions de langues bibliques with [[Jean Margain]] and at l'Institut des langues anciennes l'[[\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure (Paris)]] with [[Jean-Claude Haelewyck]] and [[Georges Bohas]].<ref name=CV/> In 2005, he obtained a [[Master in Science|Sc.M.]] of Archaeology and History of Ancient Worlds at the Biblioth\u00e8que de la Maison de l'Orient Universit\u00e9 Lyon 2 entitled: ''L'\u0153il de l'histoire: la chronologie. Les \u00e9clipses dans l'antiquit\u00e9: approche scientifique d'une chronologie absolue''.<ref name=CV/><ref name=ORCID/>\n\nIn 2007 Gertoux presented his completed [[thesis]] ''Scientific approach to an absolute chronology thanks to synchronisms dated by astronomy'' for graduate as [[PhD]] in Archaeology and History of Ancient World at [[Lumi\u00e8re University Lyon 2]],<ref name=OSCEnHRWF/><ref name=themitchellfirm/><ref name=Walsh/> which ready to review his dissertation on December 2007, but it was rejected, according to him, [[Coordination des Associations & Particuliers pour la Libert\u00e9 de Conscience]], [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] and [[Human Rights Without Frontiers]], because of his religious affiliation to Jehovah's Witnesses.<ref name=OSCEnHRWF/><ref name = CAPLC>{{cite web|publisher=Coordination des Associations & Particuliers pour la Libert\u00e9 de Conscience|title=Discrimination \u00e0 l'universit\u00e9|url=http://www.coordiap.com/tribune-libre-discrimination-universite-9911.htm}}</ref><ref name=CV/><ref name=themitchellfirm/> Michale Thomas (writer of [[Reachout Trust]]) affirm that Daniel Bodi (Department of Hebrew Studies at France's Institute National Langues et Civilisations Orientales), who originally agreed to supervise Gertoux's work, told him: \n\n{{quote|The main problem with your work is to find a jury that agrees to sit on your defence. The jury you proposed to me is not ready to sit for this thesis. You have to find teachers who accept the fundamentalist positions you defend [...] Despite my goodwill I can not defend you because I do not share this view. I propose that you address the faculties of fundamentalist theology Baptist like [[Vaux-sur-Seine]] or the [[Hyper-Calvinism|ultra-Calvinists]] of [[Aix-en-Provence]]. I am really sorry but I now understand the reaction of the doctoral committee of [[INALCO]]. My colleagues did not want INALCO to be labelled a fundamentalist school.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael Thomas|title=The Name of God Film, An Introduction and Commentary by Reachout Trust|url=https://www.academia.edu/35914110|date=13 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=Thomas/>}}\n\nThe Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe and Human Rights Without Frontiers report that \"on 10 February 2011 the Administrative Court of Paris (Dossier n\u00b0: 0918003/7-3) refused to validate his complaint to religious discrimination because the word \"fundamentalist\" is not mentioned in French laws.\"<ref name=OSCEnHRWF>{{cite web|author=[[Human Rights Without Frontiers]]|title=Working Session 15. Freedom of thought, conscience, religion or belief France: Laicit\u00e9, \"Sects\" and Muslim Women's Issues|website=OSCE Human Dimension Implementation Meeting|location=Warsaw|date=30 September 2015|url=https://www.osce.org/odihr/187476|accessdate=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Contributions ==\n=== The name YHWH ===\n{{main|Tetragrammaton}}\nHis most influential work is ''The Name of God Y.eH.oW.aH Which is pronounced as it is Written I_Eh_oU_Ah'',{{sfn|Gertoux|2002}}<ref>{{cite web|title=The name of God Y.eH.oW.aH which is pronounced as it is written I_Eh_oU_Ah: its story / Gertoux, Gerard|website=National Library of Australia|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/33150215}}</ref> published in 2002 by [[University Press of America]],{{sfn|''Theological Studies''|2002|pp=657}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Books Received|journal=The Catholic Biblical Quarterly|volume=65|issue=1|date=January 2003|pages=157\u2013162|publisher=Catholic Biblical Association|jstor=43724942}}</ref> which is a translation of ''Un Historique du nom divin: Un Nom Encens'' published by [[Editions L'Harmattan]].<ref>{{cite book|title=\u1e32iryat sefer: riv\u02bbon bibliyografi shel Bet ha-sefarim ha-le\u02bcumi \u1e7feha-universi\u1e6da\u02bci bi-Yerushalayim|year=2001|volume=71|issue=3\u20134|location=Jerusalem|publisher=Jewish National and University Library|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FSknAQAAIAAJ|pp=705}}</ref><ref name=Lind>{{cite web|author=Sarah Lind|title=TIC Talk 57, 2004. Newsletter of the United Bible Societies Translation Information Clearinghouse|date=2004|url=http://www.ubs-translations.org/tt/past_issues/tic_talk_57_2004/|website=United Bible Societies|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> ''Un historique du nom divin'' is the published thesis of ''\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d4 in Fame Only: A historical record of the divine name'' by [[Institut Catholique de Paris]].{{sfn|Buchanan|2005|pp=12}}\n\nProfessor R. J. Wilkinson states that G. Gertoux deepened of treatment of Tetragrammaton, the Name of God, history of its translation and pronounciation over the centuries, since Eve, to whom he confidently attributes the date of 4000 BCE, until 1900 EC.{{sfn|Wilkinson|2015|pp=38}} \n\nPavlos D. Vasileiadis (Post-Doc Researcher at Aristotle University of Thessaloniki) reports that \"according to G. Gertoux, the Greek term ''\u0399\u03b1\u03c9'' comes from the Hebrew ''[[Yahu]]'', and the Samaritan term ''\u0399\u03b1\u03b2\u03b5'' comes from the Aramaic ''Yaw''.\"{{sfn|Vasileiadis|2013|pp=13}} G. Gertoux says that the term Yahu means \"Yah Himself\",<ref>{{cite book|author=Didier Fontaine|year=2012|title=Le P52 contena-il un nomen sacrum \"pour J\u00e9sus\"?|url=https://areopage.net/PDF/P52%20%28P.%20Rylands.Gr.457%29_NominaSacra_Fontaine.pdf}}</ref> and ([[Jah|Yah]]) is an abbreviation of the name, with which the form Jehovah could still be possible, since it comes from the first and last letter of YHWH, an argument with which P. D. Vasileiadis agrees.{{sfn|Vasileiadis|2014|pp=63}} P. D. Vasileiadis also considers the work of G. Gertoux as a source that presents \"an overview of long-standing efforts to translate the Tetragrammaton into Greek\".<ref>Vasileiadis, Pavlos. [https://www.academia.edu/38647628 \"Jesus, the New Testament, and the sacred Tetragrammaton.\"] Presented at the International Biblical Conference \"Biblical Studies, West and East: Trends, Challenges, and Prospects,\" organised by the [[Ukrainian Catholic University]] (19\u201320 September 2013, Lviv, Ukraine).</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Religious Studies Review]]'', the opinion of [[Won W. Lee]] (professor of religion and Asian studies at Calvin University) of Gertoux's work is present: \n{{quote|In contrast to the long-held Jewish tradition, the author claims that the name of God in the HB should be pronounced. His claim is based on Exod 9:16, \"... to make my name resound through all the earth\" and Maimonides' work stressing the impossibility of a deep, personal relationship with a nameless God. With a survey of the historical record from \"Adam\" to the American Standard Version, Gertoux argues that the letters Y, W, H are read as the vowels I (or E), U (or O), and A. For the H, a mute e could be added in order to be better heard. The tetragrammaton, YHWH, is therefore read I-eH-U-A (Iehoua), the equivalent of YeHoWaH in Masoretic punctuation. This means that the name is to be pronounced as it is written, or according to its letters. The result is that the tetragrammaton is the only Hebrew name constituted, not of four consonants, but of four vowels, as noted by Josephus. This detailed treatment of the Name is useful for those who are interested in the history of its translation over the centuries.{{sfn|Lee|2003|pp=285}}}} \n\nDidier M. Fontaine reports that G. Gertoux \"shows how frequent the use of the Name has been, from the earliest times to around c.150, when the Jews began, both orally and in writing, to show serious reservations about the use of the divine name, especially with non-Jews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://areopage.net/blog/2015/04/07/le-nom-divin-imprononcable-gertoux-2015/|author=Didier Micka\u00ebl Fontaine|title=Le nom divin: impronon\u00e7able? (Gertoux, 2015)|website=\u03a0\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1 \u03b4\u1f72 \u03b4\u03bf\u03ba\u03b9\u03bc\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03c4\u03b5, \u03c4\u1f78 \u03ba\u03b1\u03bb\u1f78\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ad\u03c7\u03b5\u03c4\u03b5|date=7 April 2015|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nR. J. Wilkinson in his work ''Tetragrammaton: Western Christians and the Hebrew Name of God'' makes \"an attempt to chart Western Christian knowledge of the Hebrew divine name yhwh through to roughly the middle of the seventeenth century. The author intends his book as \u201ca work of history,\u201d and therefore eschews any theological comment \u201cas inappropriate\u201d (38).\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Kendall Soulen|year=2015|title=Review of Robert J. Wilkinson, Tetragrammaton: Western Christians and the Hebrew Name of God|journal=Journal of Jesuit Studies|volume=2|pp=723\u2013724|url=https://www.academia.edu/23711199}}</ref> In the introduction of his book, R. J. Wilkinson states: \"the book is intended to be a work of history, and I have thus eschewed theological comment as inappropriate. I am unaware of any previous work with the scope of this book, unless it be found among those who wish to promote (or prohibit) a devotional or liturgical use of the Tetragrammaton or hold strong views about its pronunciation and meaning\", and at the footnote of the page he points out that he considers that in the French version of G. Gertoux's book a chronological account of the tetragrammaton is offered, but \"he is primarily interested in supporting his assertion that the Tetragrammaton has always been read \"according to his letters,\" i.e. ''yhwh'' treated as ''[[matres lectionis]]'' and vocalized \"Jehovah\".\" R. J. Wilkinson adds G. Gertoux believes that \"the eclipse of the name was part of a satanic strategy and he believes that the Tetragrammaton appeared in the first New Testament texts.\"{{sfn|Wilkinson|2015|pp=38}}\n\nAnne Pasquier (Faculty of Theology and Religious Studies at Laval University) based on the book by G. Gertoux states that \"the perfume is associated with the divine name\", \"theme of good smell is linked to the name in the Bible\", and concludes that in [[Song of Songs]] 1,3: \"there is indeed a play on words in Hebrew between the expression \"your name\" (shem\u00e9ka) and \"your scented oils\" (sheman\u00e9ka), the name of God being comparable to an incense.\"{{sfn|Pasquier|2011|pp=126}}\n\n[[Fran\u00e7ois B\u0153spflug]] (professor emeritus of history of religions at the Faculty of Catholic Theology in Strasbourg ) wrote that G. Gertoux has provided \"valuable indications\" to the subject of the name of God, and suggest that \"contrary to what is said, still frequently, especially in Catholic circles, and in spite of what can be read in some scientific work of contemporary Hebraism, the prohibition of the images of God did not lead to a formal prohibition of the pronunciation of the name of God.{{sfn|Boespflug|2007|pp=74}} In a footnote F. B\u0153spflug thanks: \"I warmly thank G\u00e9rard Gertoux who with his availability brought this theme to my attention and provided me with valuable indications (which I will use below); cfr. G. Gertoux, '' Un historique du Nom divin - un Nom encens, Paris 1999.\"{{sfn|Boespflug|2007|pp=74}}\n\nInfluential professor [[Bruce M. Metzger]] call the Gertoux's web page as a \"further scholarly information on the origins of sacred names.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Bruce M. Metzger|title=New Bibles for the Meeting House|url=http://www.opmh.org/newbibles.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050408213316/www.opmh.org/newbibles.htm|date=2003-06-18|archive-date=2005-04-08|url-status=dead|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==== Vocalization ====\nG. Gertoux has proposed that the pronunciation of the name of God YHWH, has never been lost, and this is [[Yehowah]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Name of God Y.eH.oW.aH Which is Pronounced as it is Written I Eh oU Ah. Its Story|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|url=https://rowman.com/ISBN/9780761822042/The-Name-of-God-Y.eH.oW.aH-Which-is-Pronounced-as-it-is-Written-I-Eh-oU-Ah-Its-Story}}</ref> Philippe Barbey analyze Gertoux's arguments about pronunciation.{{sfn|Barbey|2003|pp=19}}\n\nAccording to G. Gertoux, [[Charles Perrot]], (emeritus professor of [[Institut Catholique de Paris]]) said him in a letter that \"remarks on the pronunciation of YHWH seem very relevant to me, even if, currently, it is in practice a little difficult to \"back off\" , without giving the impression of giving in to Jehovah's Witnesses.\"<ref name = CAPLC/>\n\nThomas D. Ross, (professor at the Biblical Institute of the Baptist Church in Mukwonago (Wisconsin)), agrees with G. Gertoux, who states that the Masoretic points must indicate the correct pronunciation, because it is inconceivable that God allows lose the correct pronunciation of his name, and that, despite the grammatical processes of mutation of the vowels when they are far from the accent (as ''d\u0101b\u0101r'' to the plural is made ''d\u0259b\u0101r\u012bm''). T. D. Ross considers significant, like Gertoux, that the theophoric names do not contain the vowels of Yahweh but those of [[Jehovah]].<ref>{{cite document|author=Thomas D. Ross|title=Trinitarianism Syllabus|citeseerx=10.1.1.694.8315}}</ref> T. D. Ross also considers the work of G. Gertoux as \"to defend the traditional translation of the Tetragrammaton.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Thomas D. Ross|title=The Canonicity of the Received Bible Established from Reformation and Post-Reformation Baptist Confessions|url=https://faithsaves.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/CanonicityoftheTRSeeninBaptistConfessions.pdf}}</ref>\n\nRen Manetti follows G. Gertoux on the idea that he \"postulated that the perpetual qere was not for Adonai, but for Shema\", and considers that some have recently pointed out \"a number of problems with [[Wilhelm Gesenius|Gesenius]]'s theory.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Origins of Adonai in the Hebrew Scriptures|author=Ren Manetti|url=https://www.academia.edu/4428591}}</ref>\n\nDaniel Faivre calls Yahweh the most frequent vocalization, \"but considers that it is not formally consolidated\" and therefore prefers to \"use the tetragrammaton in its consonant integrity\" and then quotes the work of G. Gertoux in its French version as \"a more complete study.\"{{sfn|Faivre|2007|pp=13}}\n\nIn observations of [[4Q120]] and some Hebrew words among some scrolls, [[George Wesley Buchanan]] (Professor Emeritus at Wesley Theological Seminary) claim that \"for many years scholars have mistakenly assumed that the Tetragrammaton was to be correctly pronounced ''Y\u00e1h-weh'', treating the central vowel as if it were a consonant. This error has recently been corrected.\"{{sfn|Buchanan|2005|pp=11}} G. W. Buchanan thinks that there are arguments for the pronounciation Yahowah, but agrees with G. Gertoux in that \"based on this data, the divine name will be spelled arbitrarily ''Yehowah''.{{sfn|Buchanan|2005|pp=12}}\n\nSarah Lind reports the study of Gertoux and say that \"G. maintains a website with excerpts at divinename.net.\": G\u00e9rard Gertoux. 2002. The Name of God Y.EH.OW.AH Which is Pronounced as It is Written I_Eh_oU_Ah: Its Story. University Press of America. Translated from the French Un historique du nom divin. Un Nom Encens (L\u2019Harmattan, 1999). G. follows Maimonides\u2019 teaching that that YHWH \u201cis read as it is written,\u201d i.e., yehua, in the same way that yhwdh is vocalized yehuda\u2014applying the (coincidentally correct) Masoretic vowels. G. first considers biblical treatment of \u201cthe name\u201d: the power of the name; to know God\u2019s name; Jesus, Satan, the controversy over the name; and \u201cthe name read distinctly\u201d (reconstruction of the reading). Part 2 examines the historical record from Adam to the American Standard Version, and the name of Jesus and its connections to the name. There is a seven part appendix that includes \u201cinterpretation of the Hebrew names\u201d and \u201clack of nomina sacra in the earliest Christian papyrus.\u201d G. maintains a website with excerpts at divinename.net.\"<ref name=Lind/>\n\n==== New Testament ====\n{{main|Names and titles of God in the New Testament}}\nD. Fontaine and R. J. Wilkinson affirm that G. Gertoux is one of who have proposed that in the autograph manuscripts of some works subsequently collected to form the New Testament the Tetragrammaton or related form was found.{{sfn|Wilkinson|2015|pp=38}}{{sfn|Wilkinson|2015|pp=94}}{{sfn|Fontaine|2007|}} G. Gertoux speculated that in [[Papyrus 52]] in the place of the term 'Lord' \"the tetragram was written in full\", but in [[Papyrus 90]], \"when the ''sacred name'' was absent the word \u2018Lord\u2019 had to be written without abbreviation.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=252}}\n\n==== Some citations in bibliographies ====\nIn ''[[The Encyclopedia of Christianity]]'' by emeritus professors [[Geoffrey W. Bromiley]], emeritus professor [[Jaroslav Pelikan]], full professor [[Jan Milic Lochman]], honorary professor [[Erwin Fahlbusch]], and writer [[John Mbiti]], (published by [[Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing]] and by [[Brill Publishers|Brill]]) the work ''The name of God Y.eH.oW.aH which is pronounced as it is written I_Eh_oU_Ah: its story '' was selected as one of the ten references under the title [[Yahweh]], in which it presents among other things textual, archaeological and theological aspects, etc.{{sfn|''The Encyclopedia of Christianity''|2008|pp=823-824}}\n\nMichael Gilligan (Catholic biblical scholar) quotes G. Gertoux to affirm that \"in the world of the Bible, however, a person's name was expected to be as meaningful as possible,\"<ref name=Gilligan>{{cite web|author=Michael Gilligan|publisher=American Catholic Press|title=The Tetragrammaton in God's Word and Liturgy|url=https://www.americancatholicpress.org/Father_Gilligan_The_Tetragrammaton.html}}</ref> M. Gilligan states: \"because God is wondrous and mighty\u2014an object of awe\u2014the name of God would also be wondrous and mighty, intended to be spoken or sung with reverence. In a biblical culture, the name of God would express God\u2019s majesty and power\" and adds: \"to put it in other terms, a biblical name (in a sense) was an alter ego; it represented the person. To know someone\u2019s name was to know who and what the person was: not only his or her character or qualities, but especially his or her power, role, or function\u2014what the individual was empowered to do. To be without a name was to be worthless, of no importance.\"<ref name=Gilligan/>\n\n==== Some comments of his thesis ====\nE. J. Revell (Professor emeritus at the [[University of Toronto]]) claim: I was very interested to read the copy of your work which you sent me. Before reading your study, had no particular opinion on the pronunciation of the name of God. As a student in the 50\u2019s, I was told that scholars have determined that \u201cYahweh\u201d was the ancient pronunciation. I did not find the argument wellgrounded, but the view was held almost as an article of faith by my instructors, and I had no superior argument, so I ignored the problem. I have occasionally thought about it since, but I have not acquired any information that you have not noticed in your study. You have certainly collected more information on the question than any other study I know, and you are to be congratulated on the production of a valuable work. Many thanks for sending it to me.{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VII}}\n\n[https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henri_Cazelles H. Cazelles] (Director of the [[Institut Catholique de Paris]]): \"Thank you very much for sending me your \"In Fame only?\" a wealth of documentation. I will deposit it at the Biblical Library for the greatest benefit of the researchers ... With my congratulations and thanks.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VII}}\n\nD. C. Hopkins (Editor of the [[Near Eastern Archaeology]]): \"Thank you for submitting your rich and detailed study. Your topic is fascinating.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VII}}\n\n[[G. W. Buchanan]] (Editor of the Mellen Biblical Commentary and emeritus professor): \"Let me thank you very much for sending me your excellent thesis. I trust that will soon have it published.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VII}}\n\n[[Shlomo Morag]] (Professor at the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]): \"The study is full of important evidence and gives a good survey of the research.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VII}}\n\n[[Edward Lipi\u0144ski (orientalist)|E. Lipinski]] (Professor, at the [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]]): \"I want to thank you for this sending and to congratulate you for the conscientious work of which this research makes proof. I'll be sure to use it if I ever come back to it.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VII-VIII}}\n\nM. Harl (Professor at the [[Universit\u00e9 de Paris IV]] Sorbonne, translator and editor of the Bible d'Alexandrie): \"Your sending fills me with admiration [...] Once again all my congratulations.\"\n\n[[J. Bott\u00e9ro]] (Director at the E.P.H.E. assyrian department): \"You seem to me both very informed and very demanding: you will get out of it and we will do a great job, which will teach me a lot! (...) You have a beautiful subject of work: I would love to see your thesis appear and read. You may be the one solving the puzzles.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VIII}}\n\n[[E. A. Livingstone]] (Doctor at the [[Oxford University]]): \"I sent your kind letter and the copy of your thesis to one of my colleagues who gave me much guidance over Old Testament material in the third edition of the [[Oxford Dictionary]] of the Christian Church (\u2026), telling me that he found your thesis most interesting; he said your case was reasonable one, and well argued.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VIII}}\n\n[[D. N. Freedman]] (Editor of the [[Anchor Bible]]): \"I was pleased to hear from you and to have your detailed treatment of this valuable and interesting subject, on which I have written from time to time. I have never been entirely atisfied with my own analysis and interpretation of the divine name in the Hebrew Bible, or with that of others, including my own teacher, [[W. F. Albright]] and his teacher (from whom Albright derived his position), [[Paul Haupt]]. At the same time, I haven\u2019t seen anything to persuade me of the superior value of another interpretation, but I will be glad to learn from your study and perhaps discover that you have finally solved this long-standing puzzle.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VIII}}\n\n==== Antithesis ====\nSteven Ortlepp, in his work ''Pronunciation of the Tetragrammaton: A Historico-Linguistic Approach'' argues against his ideas.<ref>{{cite book|author=Steven Ortlepp|title=Pronunciation of the Tetragrammaton: A Historico-Linguistic Approach|year=2011|isbn=9781445272207|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k9JEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA25|pp=25\u201326}}</ref>\n\nEgyptologist [[John Laurence Gee]] (Research Professor of Egyptology at the Neal A. Maxwell Institute for Religious Scholarship) makes a brief review, and agrees with G. Gertoux in \"that the current consensus is unconvincing\" but on the contrary, he finds his \"arguments more passionate than persuasive\", and thus he \"also find his conclusions ultimately unconvincing.\"{{sfn|Gee|2004|}} Gertoux and Gee has been indexed in ''[[Elenchus of Biblica]]''<ref>{{cite book|author=Pontificio Istituto biblico|title=Elenchus of Biblica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IpfgAAAAMAAJ|publisher=Editrice Pontificio Istituto biblico|year=2004|volume=20}}\n</ref>\n\n=== Ancient World chronologies ===\nHe has proposed Assyrian and biblical chronologies,<ref name=Oxford>{{cite web|title=Oxford Postgraduate Conference in Assyriology 2015|publisher=The British Institute for the Study of Iraq|url=http://www.bisi.ac.uk/content/oxford-postgraduate-conference-assyriology-2015|accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=iaassyriology>{{cite web|last=Gertoux|first=G\u00e9rard|title=Scientific approach to an absolute chronology through synchronisms dated by astronomy|date=20 January 2014|location=Leiden University|publisher=IAA Assyriology|url=https://iaassyriology.com/gertoux-gerard-lyonfrance-approche-scientifique-dune-chronologie-absolue-grace-aux-synchronismes-dates-par-lastronomie-scientific-approach-absolute-chronology-synchronisms-date/}}</ref> of which, according to [[Hermann Hunger]] (Professor emeritus of Assyriology at the [[University of Vienna]]), G. Gertoux \"offers new conclusions or refutes chronologies proposed by other scholars\".<ref name=ORCID>{{cite web|url=http://orcid.org/0000-0001-5916-0445|website=ORCID|title=Gerard Gertoux}}</ref>\n\n==== Dating of Herod's death ====\n{{main|Herod the Great#Death}}\nG. Gertoux is another one who propose that [[Herod the Great]] did not die in 4 BCE, as generally accepted, but in 1 BCE.<ref name=Bioul>{{cite book|author=Bruno Bioul|title=Le recensement de Quirinius, Essai d'harmonisation des donn\u00e9es lucaniennes et jos\u00e9phiennes|pp=5|url=https://www.academia.edu/36428038}}</ref> Bruno Bioul writes that \"breaking with this consensus in the 1960s, several specialists believe that Herod would have died only in 2 or 1 BC. J.-C. See G. GERTOUX, 2015.\"<ref name=Bioul/>\n\nAccording to Giuseppe Veneziano \"the dating of [[Herod the Great|Herod]]'s death has become the center of a sometimes heated academic controversy\".{{sfn|Veneziano|2015|pp=20}} G. Veneziano describes several views by different scholars in which they propose that Herod's death was in 4 BCE or 1 BCE.{{sfn|Veneziano|2015|pp=20}} G. Veneziano continues and claims that in 1 BCE \"is supported, inter alia, by W. E. Filmer (Filmer 1966), [[A. E. Steinmann]] (Steinmann 2009), and by Gerard Gertoux (Gertoux s.d.)\", and he adds that \"however, [[Josephus]] himself, although very precise in describing the events, is a little less precise in their chronological framework and - as G. Gertoux (Gertoux 2010) recalls - provides us with at least a dozen information that contribute to making it inadequate or doubtful this date.\"{{sfn|Veneziano|2015|pp=20}} Then G. Veneziano follows to A. Steinmann and G. Gertoux: \"this and other anachronisms, widely discussed by Gertoux and by Steinmann in their writings (complete with schematics), would seem to demonstrate how the date of 1 BC it is more coherent than that which places Herod's death in 4 BC. However, without preconceptions, we now evaluate both hypotheses also from an astronomical and biblical point of view.\"{{sfn|Veneziano|2015|pp=21}}\n\n==== Dating Xerxes and Artaxerxes ====\nIn response to Gerard Gertoux, (2018). ''Dating  the  reigns  of  Xerxes  and  Artaxerxes'' in: Proceedings  of  the  61e Rencontre Assyriologique Internationale, Geneva and Bern, 22\u201326 June 2015, Peter J. Huber wrote: \"traditionally, it is assumed that Xerxes died in the year 465 BC. Recently, G\u00e9rard Gertoux (2018) has argued for a 10 years higher date. As explained in his abstract, he bases that date primarily on the Babylonian eclipse text BM 32234. Unfortunately, as I shall show in the following, a more careful scrutiny of that text does not support the higher date,\"{{sfn|Huber|2019|pp=143-147}} and that \"all eclipse observations of BM 32234 Rev. are compatible with calculations for the low chronology (death of Xerxes in 465 BCE). But at least five of them flatly contradict the calculations for Gertoux\u2019s higher chronology.\"{{sfn|Huber|2019|pp=143-147}} Gertoux reacts and publish an abstract of his work to refute Huber.{{sfn|Gertoux|2019|pp=179}}\n\n==== Carthage ====\n{{main|Carthage}}\n[[Stel Pavlou]] reports that \"Gerard Gertoux argues that recent discoveries push this date back to at least 870 BC if not further. Prior to that, the Roman poet, Silius Italicus (100-200 AD), tells us that according to legend the land there had been occupied by Pelasgians\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Carthage|date=June 6, 2010|website=Atlantipedia. An A-Z Guide To The Search For Plato's Atlantis|url=https://atlantipedia.ie/samples/tag/gerard-gertoux/|author=Stel Pavlou}}</ref>\n\n==== Lectures ====\nG. Gertoux has presented conferences at different universities:\n* \u20142011, Lecture at [[University of Edinburgh]]: ''A New Achaemenid King: Darius B, owing to Synchronized Chronology''.\n* \u20142015, Lecture at [[Oxford University]]: [https://oxfordassyriology.wordpress.com/gerard-gertoux-university-of-lyon-2/ ''Assyrian and biblical chronologies: are they reliable?''],<ref name=Oxford/>\n* \u20142015, Lecture at [[Geneva University]]: [http://rai.unibe.ch/wp-content/uploads/PDF/RAI_Programme.pdf ''Dating the Reigns of Xerxes and Artaxerxes''] which was published in 2018 in: [http://www.peeters-leuven.be/boekoverz.asp?nr=10732 Orbis Biblicus et Orientalis Series Archaeologica], 40, pp. 179-206.\n* \u20142019, Invitation at the [[Coll\u00e8ge de France]] by [[Dominique Charpin]] in order to promote his thesis [https://www.academia.edu/41022774 ''Scientific approach to an absolute chronology through synchronisms dated by astronomy''], July 11th, 2019, for the [https://rai2019.digitorient.com/en/posters/ 65th Rencontre Assyriologique Internationale \u2014 the annual conference of the International Association for Assyriology].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Text and Image: Proceedings of the 61e Rencontre Assyriologique Internationale, Geneva and Bern, 22-26 June 2015|year=2018|editor1=Attinger, Pascal|editor2=Cavigneaux, Antoine|editor3=Mittermayer, Catherine|editor4=Nov\u00e0k, Mirko|doi=10.5167/uzh-157125|location=Leuven, Belgium|publisher=Peeters Publishers|author1=S.N}}</ref>\n* \u20142019, invitation at [[American Schools of Oriental Research]], (ASOR) Annual Meeting, The Westin San Diego, San Diego, California with the subject \"Archaeology and Biblical Studies I\". Chair: [[Jonathan Rosenbaum (scholar)]]. November 20\u201323.<ref>{{cite book|title=ASOR PROGRAM GUIDE|date=November 2019|location=San Diego, California|publisher=American School of Oriental Research, 2019 Annual Meeting|isbn=978-0-89757-114-2|url=http://www.asor.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/2019-ASOR-Program-and-Abstract-Book.pdf}}</ref>\n\n=== Historicities ===\n==== Historicity of the Trojan War ====\n{{main|Trojan War}}\nIn the journal ''Antrocom Online Journal of Anthropology'', Xaris M. Koutelakis (awarded 2 times by the Academy of Athens and the Ministry of Culture) says that \"known archaeological data are thoroughly reexamined.\"{{sfn|Koutelakis|2007|pp=117}} He states:\n\n{{quote|On the other hand, special ceremonies had been taking place in Delos since the 12th century B.C., when, following the dispersion of the naval groups in which they had participated (that is, the Peoples of the Sea), Lycian mariners, tradesmen and pirates chose Delos as an ultimate refuge (Koutelakis, X. 2014: 96 n. 43, 44) for the safekeeping of their loot and profits, perhaps having previously destroyed Koukounaries in Paros, Grotta in Naxos, Phylakope in Melos and Hagia Eirene in Kea (Gertoux G., 2015: 37-38), and captured the inhabitants of the undefended Daskaleio-Keros or forced them to abandon their island.{{sfn|Koutelakis|2007|pp=117}}}}\n\n==== Walls of the Ruler ====\n{{main|Walls-of-the-Ruler}}\nAccording to egyptologian Jozef Hudec (Research Executive at Slovak Academy of Sciences) and Miroslav \u010cern\u00fd \"it could have contained realistic topography\" in [[story of Sinuhe]].{{sfn|Hudec|\u010cern\u00fd|2018|pp=30}} They propose that \"the Wall of the Ruler could have been assumed in Wadi Tumilat (at Tell el-Retaba, which might be the point in the defence line/wall closest to Gebel el-Ahmar), if Sinuhe could have achieved almost 90 km during one November day.\"{{sfn|Hudec|\u010cern\u00fd|2018|pp=30}} They adds: \n{{quote|The 7th day of the 3rd month of inundation (LICHTHEIM, M. Ancient Egyptian Literature. Vol. I: The Old and Middle Kingdoms, p. 223) would have been in November during the rule of [[Amenemhet I]]/[[Senwosret  I]]. (GERTOUX, G. Absolute Chronology of the Ancient World from 2840 BCE to 1533 BCE, p. 39). The length of day (between sunrise and sunset) in November is more than 10 hours, cf. Timeanddate.com, available from https://www.timeanddate.com/sun/egypt/cairo [cit. 6 January 2018]{{sfn|Hudec|\u010cern\u00fd|2018|pp=30}}}}\n\n==== Historicity of Exodus ====\n{{main|The Exodus}}\nG. Gertoux affirms the exact historicity of the [[Book of Exodus]].<ref name=Snyder/> David A. Snyder affirm that \"under the Gertoux timeline, the Hebrews would have been slaves from 1530 to 1476 BC, which is when the Exodus occurred and is enough time for God to direct Moses to tell Pharaoh to ''set my people free''.<ref name=Snyder>{{cite book|title=Abraham of Ur: A Critical Analysis of the Life and Times of the Patriarch|author=David A. Snyder|year=2015|isbn=9781491777268|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QC3fCgAAQBAJ&pg=P128}}</ref> D. A. Snyder suggest: \"the reason I give such high regard for the Gertoux timeline is the highly documented research that he uses in his ''ancient chronological system'' of study. His work equates the Hebrews with the Hyksos with some certainty.<ref name=Snyder/>\n\n=== Hebrew terms ===\n[[Ola Wikander]] (professor at Lund University) \"discuss two cases of seeming \"irregularity\" in the Tiberian [[Masoretic]] stop and fricative systems, especially concerning the relationship between those two systems \u2014and to ponder the methodological implications of this for the study of Masoretic orthography and analysis.\"{{sfn|Wikander|2019|pp=125-166}} He wrote that \"The name Ti\u00f0\u02bf\u0101l, which appears in Gen 14:1, has been plausibly explained as a borrowed Hebrew version of the Hittite royal name Tud\u1e2baliya.\"\n\n{{quote|A recent publication supporting the identification with Tud\u1e2bula (which ultimately goes back to [[Theophilus Pinches|T. G. Pinches]] in 1897) is G\u00e9rard Gertoux, Abraham and Chedorlaomer: Chronological, Historical and Archaeological Evidence (sineloco,2015), 34 (etpassim). One may note with some interest that Sayce actually suggests identifying Tud\u1e2baliya with the Tud\u1e2bula of the Spartoli tablet sin his early comment (or Tudghula, as he writes the latter), and indeed uses that purported identification as a step in arguing the connection between the Hittite name and Genesis 14!{{sfn|Wikander|2019|pp=125-166}}}}\n\n== Works ==\n* {{cite book|title=Un Historique du nom divin: Un Nom Encens|author=G\u00e9rard Gertoux|publisher=Editions L'Harmattan|date=1 August 1999|isbn=9782296391994|oclc=716841963}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Name of God Y.eH.oW.aH Which is Pronounced as it is Written I_Eh_oU_Ah. It Story|author=G\u00e9rard Gertoux|publisher=University Press of America|year=2002|isbn=9780761822042|series=G - Reference, Information and Interdisciplinary Subjects Series|oclc=59502233}}\n* {{cite book|title=Guds navns historie|author=G\u00e9rard Gertoux|publisher=K\u00f8benhavn: Gramma|year=2005|isbn=87-990125-6-1|oclc=473717946}}\n* {{cite book|title=Storia del nome di Dio. Un recente studio che f\u00e0 luce sulla corretta pronuncia del sacro nome|author=G\u00e8rard Gertoux|editor=S. Pizzorni|translator1=G. Gabrielli|translator2=M. Aragone|publisher=Azzurra 7|year=2007|isbn=9788888907093}}\n* {{cite book|title=Le nom divin dans le nouveau testament|series=Religions et Spiritualit\u00e9|author=Didier Micka\u00ebl Fontaine|publisher=Editions L'Harmattan|year=2007|isbn=9782296176096|oclc=300408308}}, (preface of G\u00e9rard Gertoux).\n* {{Cite AV media|people=Fritz Poppenberg|title=The Name of God|date=2014|publisher=Drei Linden Film}}\n* {{cite book|title=\u0418\u043c\u044f \u0411\u043e\u0433\u0430: \u0435\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u043d\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435|author=\u0416\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0440 \u0416\u0435\u0440\u0442\u043e|location=Kiev|publisher=Strelbytskyy Multimedia Publishing|date=2 February 2018|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EBtKDwAAQBAJ}}\n* {{cite book|title=Text and image: proceedings of the 61e Rencontre Assyriologique Internationale, Geneva and Bern, 22-26 June 2015|editor=Pascal Attinger|author=G\u00e9rard Gertoux|editor2=Attinger P.|editor3=Cavigneaux A.|editor4=Mittermayer C.|editor5=Novak M.|publisher=Leuven; Bristol, CT: Peeters Publishers|year=2018|series=Orbis biblicus et orientalis., Series Archaeologica|volume=Vol. 40|isbn=978-90-429-3713-0|oclc=1046070112}}\n\nSome other selfpublished works are found in [[Semantic Scholar]]'s web page and [[ORCID]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Gerard Gertoux|website=Semantic Scholar|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/Gerard-Gertoux/108067232}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book|title=Les t\u00e9moins de Jehovah: Pour un christianisme original|series=Religion et sciences humaines|first=Philippe|last=Barbey|publisher=[[Editions L'Harmattan]]|year=2003|isbn=9782296315914|pp=19|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-W9Ul5pFIOQC&pg=PA19|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=La caricatura e il sacro: Islam, ebraismo e cristianisimo a confronto|series=Transizioni (Vita e pensiero (Firm)|volume=Vol. 21|first=Fran\u00e7ois|last=Boespflug|publisher=Vita e Pensiero|year=2007|isbn=9788834313824|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=98H0BCqPhcAC&pg=PA74|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=Yahweh|work=The Encyclodedia of Christianity|volume=Vol 5|series=The Encyclopedia of Christianity|editor1=[[Geoffrey William Bromiley|Bromiley, Geoffrey William]]|editor2=[[Erwin Fahlbusch]]|editor3=[[Jan Milic Lochman]]|editor4=[[John Mbiti]]|editor5=[[Jaroslav Pelikan]]|translator=Geoffrey William Bromiley|editor6=[[Jaroslav Pelikan]]|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|year=2008|isbn=9780802824172|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lZUBZlth2qgC&pg=PA823|pp=823\u2013824|ref={{harvid|The Encyclopedia of Christianity|2008}}}}\n*{{cite book|title=The Book of Daniel|first=George Wesley|last=Buchanan|series=Mellen Biblical Commentary: Old Testament|volume=Vol. 25|publisher=Wipf and Stock Publishers|year=2005|isbn=9781592440214|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5NFKAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA12|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=Mythes de la Gen\u00e8se, gen\u00e8se des mythes|series=Religions et Spiritualit\u00e9|first=Daniel|last=Faivre|publisher=Editions L'Harmattan|year=2007|isbn=9782296174580|pp=13|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AtThi9y-imcC&pg=PA13|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first=Didier Micka\u00ebl|last=Fontaine|year=2007|title=Le nom divin dans le nouveau testament|lang=fr|location=Paris|publisher=Editions L'Harmattan|isbn=978-2296176096|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|title=Gertoux, G\u00e9rard. The Name of God Y.EH.OW.AH Which is Pronounced as It Is Written I_EH_OU_AH. Lanham, Md.: University Press of America, 2002. Pp. 328. Paper. $47.00. ISBN 0761822046|first=John Laurence|last=Gee|journal=Review of Biblical Literature|date=June 2004|url=https://www.bookreviews.org/pdf/3317_3709.pdf|publisher=Society of Biblical Literature|issn=1099-0321|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Gertoux|first=Gerard|year=2002|title=The Name of God Y.eH.oW.aH Which is pronounced as it is Written I_Eh_oU_Ah. Its history|translator=Terry Costanzo|series=G - Reference, Information and Interdisciplinary Subjects Series|location=Lanham, MD|publisher=University Press of America|isbn=978-0-7618-2204-2|oclc=59502233|url=https://www.academia.edu/41431232|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Gertoux|first=G\u00e9rard|date=December 2019|journal=Nouvelles Assyriologiques Br\u00e8ves et Utilitaires|issue=4|issn=0989-5671|title=NOTES BR\u00c8VES. Dating the Reigns of Xerxes and Artaxerxes|url=https://sepoa.fr/wp/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/NABU-2019-4-011-indexe%CC%81.pdf|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Huber|first=Peter J.|date=September 2019|journal=Nouvelles Assyriologiques Br\u00e8ves et Utilitaires|issue=3|issn=0989-5671|title=NOTES BR\u00c8VES. Dating the death of Xerxes|url=https://sepoa.fr/wp/wp-content/uploads/2019/10/NABU-2019-3-008-complet-indexe%CC%81.pdf|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|first1=Jozef|last1=Hudec|first2=Miroslav|last2=\u010cern\u00fd|publisher=Institute of Oriental Studies, Slovak Academy of Sciences|url=https://www.academia.edu/39925448|pp=30|title=Discoveries on Fortifications at Tell el-Retaba|journal=Asian and African Studies'|volume=27|issue=1|date=2018|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|first=Xaris M.|last=Koutelakis|title=The \"\u039a\u03a5\u039a\u039d\u039f\u0399\" of Delos: Alteration of the Identity of Delos*|journal=Antrocom Online Journal of Anthropology|year=2007|volume=13|number=1|issn=1973\u20132880|pp=117|url=http://www.antrocom.net/upload/sub/antrocom/130117/06-Antrocom.pdf|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|first=Won W.|last=Lee|title=Notes on Recent Publications|journal=Religious Studies Review|volume=29|issue=3|date=July 2003|pp=285|publisher=Council of Societies for the Study of Religion|location=Valparaiso University|doi=10.1111/j.1748-0922.2003.tb00391.x|issn=0319-485X|oclc=909876699|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|first=Anne|last=Pasquier|title=Mystery and Secrecy in the Nag Hammadi Collection and Other Ancient Literature: Ideas and Practices|chapter=Invocation et glorification du Nom divin dans le Livre sacr\u00e9 du grand Esprit invisible ou \u00c9vangile \u00e9gyptien (NHC III,2; NHC IV,2)|work=Mystery and Secrecy in the Nag Hammadi Collection and Other Ancient Literature: Ideas and Practices: Studies for Einar Thomassen at Sixty|series=Nag Hammadi and Manichaean Studies|volume=Vol. 76|editor=Christian H. Bull|editor2=Liv Lied|editor3=John D. Turner|publisher=BRILL|year=2011|pp=126|isbn=9789004212077|doi=10.1163/9789004215122_007|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qCwaSTk5iEcC&pg=PA126|location=Leiden; Boston|oclc=794213410|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|journal=Theological Studies|title=Books Received. Scriptural Studies|date=1 September 2002|doi=10.1177/004056390206300334|volume=63|issue=3|issn=0040-5639|publisher=Baltimore|url=http://cdn.theologicalstudies.net/63/63.3/63.3.reviews-notices.pdf|ref={{harvid|Theological Studies|2002}}}}\n*{{cite journal|last=Vasileiadis|first = Pavlos D.|title = The pronunciation of the sacred Tetragrammaton: An overview of a nomen revelatus that became a nomen absconditus|journal=[[Judaica Ukrainica]]|publisher=[[National University of Kyiv-Mohyla Academy]]|volume=2|year=2013|url = http://judaicaukrainica.ukma.edu.ua/ckfinder/userfiles/files/JU_2_2013_Vasileiadis.pdf|ref = harv|pp=13}}\n*{{cite journal|title = Aspects of rendering the sacred Tetragrammaton in Greek|first = Pavlos D.|last = Vasileiadis|journal = [[Open Theology]]|volume = 1|issue = 1|year = 2014|pages = 56\u201388|url = https://www.academia.edu/10457621|location = Berlin, Germany|publisher = De Gruyter|oclc = 927128789|issn = 2300-6579|doi = 10.2478/opth-2014-0006|ref = harv}}\n*{{cite magazine|last=Veneziano|first=Giuseppe|title=L'eclisse di Erode|magazine=Osservatorio Astronomico di Genova|date=28-29 March 2015|url=https://www.alssa.it/Documenti/Seminari/17/07_-_L_eclisse_di_Erode.pdf|publisher=XVII Seminario di Archeoastronomia Associazione Ligure per lo Sviluppo degli Studi Archeoastronomici|location=Universit\u00e0 Popolare Sestrese Piazzetta dell\u2019Universit\u00e0 Popolare|language=it|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite journal|first=Ola|last=Wikander|title=Stop Being Fricative! The Hebrew \u0160\u0115w\u0101\u02beMedium, Syllabic Consonants, Tid\u02bf\u0101l and the Aesthetics of Linguistic and Exegetical Models*|journal=Svensk Exegetisk \u00c5rsbok|volume=84|year=2019|pp=125\u2013166|publisher=Swedish Collegium for Advanced Study (Uppsala) and Lund University with contributions by Aljo\u0161a \u0160orgo (University of Leiden)|url=https://www.academia.edu/38669053|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last = Wilkinson|first = Robert J.|title = Tetragrammaton: Western Christians and the Hebrew Name of God: From the Beginnings to the Seventeenth Century.|series=Studies in the History of Christian Traditions|volume = Vol. 179|date = 4 February 2015|location = Leiden|publisher = Brill|isbn = 978-90-04-28817-1|doi = 10.1163/9789004288171|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1xyoBgAAQBAJ|ref = harv}}\n\n== External links ==\n*[https://assoce.fr/waldec/W691054089/ASSOCIATION-BIBLIQUE-DE-RECHERCHE-D-ANCIENS-MANUSCRITS Association Biblique de Recherche d'Anciens Manuscrits]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gertoux, Gerard}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Tetragrammaton]]\n[[Category:Hebraists]]\n[[Category:Political repression in France]]\n[[Category:Discrimination in France]]\n[[Category:Religious discrimination]]\n[[Category:Government opposition to new religious movements]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the issue is settled -->\n{{AfDM|page=G\u00e9rard Gertoux (3rd nomination)|year=2020|month=March|day=26|substed=yes|origtag=afdx|help=off}}\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox person\n| name = G\u00e9rard Gertoux\n| birth_date =  {{Birth date and age|1955|03|19}}\n| birth_place = Lyon\n| nationality = French\n| education = [[Master of Science]]<br>[[Engineering physics]]\n| alma_mater = [[\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure d'ing\u00e9nieurs \u00e9lectriciens de Grenoble]]<br>[[Lumi\u00e8re University Lyon 2]]<br>[[\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure de Lyon]]\n| occupation = [[Writer]], [[Hebraist]], [[Tetragrammaton|Tetragram]]mist, [[Astronomist]], [[Chronologist]]\n| organization = [[The International Association for Assyriology]]<br>Association Biblique de Recherche d'Anciens Manuscrits\n| notable_works = ''The Name of God Y.eH.oW.aH Which is pronounced as it is Written I_Eh_oU_Ah''\n| movement = [[Jehovah's Witness]]\n| employer = [[French National Centre for Scientific Research]]\n}}\n'''G\u00e9rard Marcel Laurent Gertoux''' (born in 19 March 1955) is a French academic, physical engineer,<ref name=BnF/><ref name=Thomas>{{cite web|first=Michael|last=Thomas|url=https://reachouttrust.org/the-name-of-god/|title=The JW Name of God Documentary-1 Is it Independent?|date=2017-05-24|website=[[Reachout Trust]]|language=en-US|access-date=2020-02-28}}</ref> [[Hebraist]],<ref name=BnF>{{cite web|title=Notice de personne: G\u00e9rard Gertoux|website=BnF Catalogue g\u00e9n\u00e9ral|url=https://catalogue.bnf.fr/ark:/12148/cb13548516z|accessdate=March 3, 2020}}</ref><ref name=LC/><ref name=NLI/> Tetragrammist,<ref name=BnF/><ref name=LC/><ref name=NLI/> Bible scholar, [[Assyriology|Assyriologist]], historian and a researcher specializing in ancient [[near eastern archaeology]]. He is also a member of the [[International Association for Assyriology]] (IAA) and founder of ''Association Biblique de Recherche d'Anciens Manuscrits''.\n\n== Life ==\nG\u00e9rard Gertoux was born in 19 March 1955 at Lyon.<ref name=CV/> G\u00e9rard Gertoux is a [[Jehovah's witness]] since 1982.<ref name=Walsh>{{cite letter|author=William C. Walsh|subject=RE: Follow up of Rapporteur's visit to France (18-29 September 2005)|url=http://www.coordiap.com/Document/onu-2010-eng.pdf|recipient=[[Asma Jahangir]]|pp=5-6}}</ref><ref name=OSCEnHRWF/><ref name=themitchellfirm>{{cite web|title=Executive Report. France: Rising Government Restrictions on Religion|website=themitchellfirm.com|date=October 17, 2011|url=http://www.aicongress.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/05/France-Executive-Summary-October17.2011.pdf}}</ref> G. Gertoux has been president since 1991 of the Association Biblique de Recherche d'Anciens Manuscrits.<ref>{{cite web|title=le Nom de Dieu en question: \u00abLe Seigneur a dit \u00e0 mon Seigneur [sic !]: 'Assieds-toi \u00e0 ma droite, Jusqu'\u00e0 ce que je fasse de tes ennemis ton marchepied\" (Louis Segond, Mt, 22,44)|date=22 June 2007|url=http://actua.unitariennes.over-blog.com/article-10984645.html}}</ref> From 2012 he become a member of the International Association for Assyriology.<ref name=CV/><ref name=iaassyriology/><ref name=ORCID/>\n\n=== Education ===\nHe obtained a diploma [[Engineering physics|Physical Engineering]] at [[\u00c9cole nationale sup\u00e9rieure d'ing\u00e9nieurs \u00e9lectriciens de Grenoble]] (I.N.P.G.) in 1979.{{sfn|Gee|2004|}}<ref name=BnF/><ref name=CV>{{cite web|url=https://univ-lyon2.academia.edu/GerardGERTOUX/CurriculumVitae|title=Curriculum Vitae|author=Gertoux, G\u00e9rard}}</ref> In 1985, he obtained a CAPES in Physics to become a certified professor.<ref name=BnF/><ref name=LC>{{cite web|website=Library of Congress|title=G\u00e9rard Gertoux|accessdate=March 30, 2020|url=http://id.loc.gov/authorities/names/n2002090734.html}}</ref><ref name=NLI>{{cite web|title=G\u00e9rard Gertoux|website=National Library of Israel|accessdate=March 30, 2020|url=http://uli.nli.org.il/F/?func=direct&doc_number=000052631&local_base=nlx10}}</ref> From 1992 to 1993, and 2001, he studied [[Hebrew language]] at Acad\u00e9mie des langues anciennes with Elie Cohen, at Sessions de langues bibliques with [[Jean Margain]] and at l'Institut des langues anciennes l'[[\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure (Paris)]] with [[Jean-Claude Haelewyck]] and [[Georges Bohas]].<ref name=CV/> In 2005, he obtained a [[Master in Science|Sc.M.]] of Archaeology and History of Ancient Worlds at the Biblioth\u00e8que de la Maison de l'Orient Universit\u00e9 Lyon 2 entitled: ''L'\u0153il de l'histoire: la chronologie. Les \u00e9clipses dans l'antiquit\u00e9: approche scientifique d'une chronologie absolue''.<ref name=CV/><ref name=ORCID/>\n\nIn 2007 Gertoux presented his completed [[thesis]] ''Scientific approach to an absolute chronology thanks to synchronisms dated by astronomy'' for graduate as [[PhD]] in Archaeology and History of Ancient World at [[Lumi\u00e8re University Lyon 2]],<ref name=OSCEnHRWF/><ref name=themitchellfirm/><ref name=Walsh/> which ready to review his dissertation on December 2007, but it was rejected, according to him, [[Coordination des Associations & Particuliers pour la Libert\u00e9 de Conscience]], [[Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe]] and [[Human Rights Without Frontiers]], because of his religious affiliation to Jehovah's Witnesses.<ref name=OSCEnHRWF/><ref name = CAPLC>{{cite web|publisher=Coordination des Associations & Particuliers pour la Libert\u00e9 de Conscience|title=Discrimination \u00e0 l'universit\u00e9|url=http://www.coordiap.com/tribune-libre-discrimination-universite-9911.htm}}</ref><ref name=CV/><ref name=themitchellfirm/> Michale Thomas (writer of [[Reachout Trust]]) affirm that Daniel Bodi (Department of Hebrew Studies at France's Institute National Langues et Civilisations Orientales), who originally agreed to supervise Gertoux's work, told him: \n\n{{quote|The main problem with your work is to find a jury that agrees to sit on your defence. The jury you proposed to me is not ready to sit for this thesis. You have to find teachers who accept the fundamentalist positions you defend [...] Despite my goodwill I can not defend you because I do not share this view. I propose that you address the faculties of fundamentalist theology Baptist like [[Vaux-sur-Seine]] or the [[Hyper-Calvinism|ultra-Calvinists]] of [[Aix-en-Provence]]. I am really sorry but I now understand the reaction of the doctoral committee of [[INALCO]]. My colleagues did not want INALCO to be labelled a fundamentalist school.<ref>{{cite book|author=Michael Thomas|title=The Name of God Film, An Introduction and Commentary by Reachout Trust|url=https://www.academia.edu/35914110|date=13 February 2018}}</ref><ref name=Thomas/>}}\n\nThe Organization for Security and Co-operation in Europe and Human Rights Without Frontiers report that \"on 10 February 2011 the Administrative Court of Paris (Dossier n\u00b0: 0918003/7-3) refused to validate his complaint to religious discrimination because the word \"fundamentalist\" is not mentioned in French laws.\"<ref name=OSCEnHRWF>{{cite web|author=[[Human Rights Without Frontiers]]|title=Working Session 15. Freedom of thought, conscience, religion or belief France: Laicit\u00e9, \"Sects\" and Muslim Women's Issues|website=OSCE Human Dimension Implementation Meeting|location=Warsaw|date=30 September 2015|url=https://www.osce.org/odihr/187476|accessdate=February 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Contributions ==\n=== The name YHWH ===\n{{main|Tetragrammaton}}\nHis most influential work is ''The Name of God Y.eH.oW.aH Which is pronounced as it is Written I_Eh_oU_Ah'',{{sfn|Gertoux|2002}}<ref>{{cite web|title=The name of God Y.eH.oW.aH which is pronounced as it is written I_Eh_oU_Ah: its story / Gertoux, Gerard|website=National Library of Australia|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/33150215}}</ref> published in 2002 by [[University Press of America]],{{sfn|''Theological Studies''|2002|pp=657}}<ref>{{cite journal|title=Books Received|journal=The Catholic Biblical Quarterly|volume=65|issue=1|date=January 2003|pages=157\u2013162|publisher=Catholic Biblical Association|jstor=43724942}}</ref> which is a translation of ''Un Historique du nom divin: Un Nom Encens'' published by [[Editions L'Harmattan]].<ref>{{cite book|title=\u1e32iryat sefer: riv\u02bbon bibliyografi shel Bet ha-sefarim ha-le\u02bcumi \u1e7feha-universi\u1e6da\u02bci bi-Yerushalayim|year=2001|volume=71|issue=3\u20134|location=Jerusalem|publisher=Jewish National and University Library|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FSknAQAAIAAJ|pp=705}}</ref><ref name=Lind>{{cite web|author=Sarah Lind|title=TIC Talk 57, 2004. Newsletter of the United Bible Societies Translation Information Clearinghouse|date=2004|url=http://www.ubs-translations.org/tt/past_issues/tic_talk_57_2004/|website=United Bible Societies|accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref> ''Un historique du nom divin'' is the published thesis of ''\u05d9\u05d4\u05d5\u05d4 in Fame Only: A historical record of the divine name'' by [[Institut Catholique de Paris]].{{sfn|Buchanan|2005|pp=12}}\n\nProfessor R. J. Wilkinson states that G. Gertoux deepened of treatment of Tetragrammaton, the Name of God, history of its translation and pronounciation over the centuries, since Eve, to whom he confidently attributes the date of 4000 BCE, until 1900 EC.{{sfn|Wilkinson|2015|pp=38}} \n\nPavlos D. Vasileiadis (Post-Doc Researcher at Aristotle University of Thessaloniki) reports that \"according to G. Gertoux, the Greek term ''\u0399\u03b1\u03c9'' comes from the Hebrew ''[[Yahu]]'', and the Samaritan term ''\u0399\u03b1\u03b2\u03b5'' comes from the Aramaic ''Yaw''.\"{{sfn|Vasileiadis|2013|pp=13}} G. Gertoux says that the term Yahu means \"Yah Himself\",<ref>{{cite book|author=Didier Fontaine|year=2012|title=Le P52 contena-il un nomen sacrum \"pour J\u00e9sus\"?|url=https://areopage.net/PDF/P52%20%28P.%20Rylands.Gr.457%29_NominaSacra_Fontaine.pdf}}</ref> and ([[Jah|Yah]]) is an abbreviation of the name, with which the form Jehovah could still be possible, since it comes from the first and last letter of YHWH, an argument with which P. D. Vasileiadis agrees.{{sfn|Vasileiadis|2014|pp=63}} P. D. Vasileiadis also considers the work of G. Gertoux as a source that presents \"an overview of long-standing efforts to translate the Tetragrammaton into Greek\".<ref>Vasileiadis, Pavlos. [https://www.academia.edu/38647628 \"Jesus, the New Testament, and the sacred Tetragrammaton.\"] Presented at the International Biblical Conference \"Biblical Studies, West and East: Trends, Challenges, and Prospects,\" organised by the [[Ukrainian Catholic University]] (19\u201320 September 2013, Lviv, Ukraine).</ref>\n\nIn ''[[Religious Studies Review]]'', the opinion of [[Won W. Lee]] (professor of religion and Asian studies at Calvin University) of Gertoux's work is present: \n{{quote|In contrast to the long-held Jewish tradition, the author claims that the name of God in the HB should be pronounced. His claim is based on Exod 9:16, \"... to make my name resound through all the earth\" and Maimonides' work stressing the impossibility of a deep, personal relationship with a nameless God. With a survey of the historical record from \"Adam\" to the American Standard Version, Gertoux argues that the letters Y, W, H are read as the vowels I (or E), U (or O), and A. For the H, a mute e could be added in order to be better heard. The tetragrammaton, YHWH, is therefore read I-eH-U-A (Iehoua), the equivalent of YeHoWaH in Masoretic punctuation. This means that the name is to be pronounced as it is written, or according to its letters. The result is that the tetragrammaton is the only Hebrew name constituted, not of four consonants, but of four vowels, as noted by Josephus. This detailed treatment of the Name is useful for those who are interested in the history of its translation over the centuries.{{sfn|Lee|2003|pp=285}}}} \n\nDidier M. Fontaine reports that G. Gertoux \"shows how frequent the use of the Name has been, from the earliest times to around c.150, when the Jews began, both orally and in writing, to show serious reservations about the use of the divine name, especially with non-Jews.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://areopage.net/blog/2015/04/07/le-nom-divin-imprononcable-gertoux-2015/|author=Didier Micka\u00ebl Fontaine|title=Le nom divin: impronon\u00e7able? (Gertoux, 2015)|website=\u03a0\u03ac\u03bd\u03c4\u03b1 \u03b4\u1f72 \u03b4\u03bf\u03ba\u03b9\u03bc\u03ac\u03b6\u03b5\u03c4\u03b5, \u03c4\u1f78 \u03ba\u03b1\u03bb\u1f78\u03bd \u03ba\u03b1\u03c4\u03ad\u03c7\u03b5\u03c4\u03b5|date=7 April 2015|accessdate=12 January 2020}}</ref>\n\nR. J. Wilkinson in his work ''Tetragrammaton: Western Christians and the Hebrew Name of God'' makes \"an attempt to chart Western Christian knowledge of the Hebrew divine name yhwh through to roughly the middle of the seventeenth century. The author intends his book as \u201ca work of history,\u201d and therefore eschews any theological comment \u201cas inappropriate\u201d (38).\"<ref>{{cite journal|author=Kendall Soulen|year=2015|title=Review of Robert J. Wilkinson, Tetragrammaton: Western Christians and the Hebrew Name of God|journal=Journal of Jesuit Studies|volume=2|pp=723\u2013724|url=https://www.academia.edu/23711199}}</ref> In the introduction of his book, R. J. Wilkinson states: \"the book is intended to be a work of history, and I have thus eschewed theological comment as inappropriate. I am unaware of any previous work with the scope of this book, unless it be found among those who wish to promote (or prohibit) a devotional or liturgical use of the Tetragrammaton or hold strong views about its pronunciation and meaning\", and at the footnote of the page he points out that he considers that in the French version of G. Gertoux's book a chronological account of the tetragrammaton is offered, but \"he is primarily interested in supporting his assertion that the Tetragrammaton has always been read \"according to his letters,\" i.e. ''yhwh'' treated as ''[[matres lectionis]]'' and vocalized \"Jehovah\".\" R. J. Wilkinson adds G. Gertoux believes that \"the eclipse of the name was part of a satanic strategy and he believes that the Tetragrammaton appeared in the first New Testament texts.\"{{sfn|Wilkinson|2015|pp=38}}\n\nAnne Pasquier (Faculty of Theology and Religious Studies at Laval University) based on the book by G. Gertoux states that \"the perfume is associated with the divine name\", \"theme of good smell is linked to the name in the Bible\", and concludes that in [[Song of Songs]] 1,3: \"there is indeed a play on words in Hebrew between the expression \"your name\" (shem\u00e9ka) and \"your scented oils\" (sheman\u00e9ka), the name of God being comparable to an incense.\"{{sfn|Pasquier|2011|pp=126}}\n\n[[Fran\u00e7ois B\u0153spflug]] (professor emeritus of history of religions at the Faculty of Catholic Theology in Strasbourg ) wrote that G. Gertoux has provided \"valuable indications\" to the subject of the name of God, and suggest that \"contrary to what is said, still frequently, especially in Catholic circles, and in spite of what can be read in some scientific work of contemporary Hebraism, the prohibition of the images of God did not lead to a formal prohibition of the pronunciation of the name of God.{{sfn|Boespflug|2007|pp=74}} In a footnote F. B\u0153spflug thanks: \"I warmly thank G\u00e9rard Gertoux who with his availability brought this theme to my attention and provided me with valuable indications (which I will use below); cfr. G. Gertoux, '' Un historique du Nom divin - un Nom encens, Paris 1999.\"{{sfn|Boespflug|2007|pp=74}}\n\nInfluential professor [[Bruce M. Metzger]] call the Gertoux's web page as a \"further scholarly information on the origins of sacred names.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Bruce M. Metzger|title=New Bibles for the Meeting House|url=http://www.opmh.org/newbibles.htm|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050408213316/www.opmh.org/newbibles.htm|date=2003-06-18|archive-date=2005-04-08|url-status=dead|access-date=2020-03-27}}</ref>\n\n==== Vocalization ====\nG. Gertoux has proposed that the pronunciation of the name of God YHWH, has never been lost, and this is [[Yehowah]].<ref>{{cite web|title=The Name of God Y.eH.oW.aH Which is Pronounced as it is Written I Eh oU Ah. Its Story|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|url=https://rowman.com/ISBN/9780761822042/The-Name-of-God-Y.eH.oW.aH-Which-is-Pronounced-as-it-is-Written-I-Eh-oU-Ah-Its-Story}}</ref> Philippe Barbey analyze Gertoux's arguments about pronunciation.{{sfn|Barbey|2003|pp=19}}\n\nAccording to G. Gertoux, [[Charles Perrot]], (emeritus professor of [[Institut Catholique de Paris]]) said him in a letter that \"remarks on the pronunciation of YHWH seem very relevant to me, even if, currently, it is in practice a little difficult to \"back off\" , without giving the impression of giving in to Jehovah's Witnesses.\"<ref name = CAPLC/>\n\nThomas D. Ross, (professor at the Biblical Institute of the Baptist Church in Mukwonago (Wisconsin)), agrees with G. Gertoux, who states that the Masoretic points must indicate the correct pronunciation, because it is inconceivable that God allows lose the correct pronunciation of his name, and that, despite the grammatical processes of mutation of the vowels when they are far from the accent (as ''d\u0101b\u0101r'' to the plural is made ''d\u0259b\u0101r\u012bm''). T. D. Ross considers significant, like Gertoux, that the theophoric names do not contain the vowels of Yahweh but those of [[Jehovah]].<ref>{{cite document|author=Thomas D. Ross|title=Trinitarianism Syllabus|citeseerx=10.1.1.694.8315}}</ref> T. D. Ross also considers the work of G. Gertoux as \"to defend the traditional translation of the Tetragrammaton.\"<ref>{{cite book|author=Thomas D. Ross|title=The Canonicity of the Received Bible Established from Reformation and Post-Reformation Baptist Confessions|url=https://faithsaves.net/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/CanonicityoftheTRSeeninBaptistConfessions.pdf}}</ref>\n\nRen Manetti follows G. Gertoux on the idea that he \"postulated that the perpetual qere was not for Adonai, but for Shema\", and considers that some have recently pointed out \"a number of problems with [[Wilhelm Gesenius|Gesenius]]'s theory.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Origins of Adonai in the Hebrew Scriptures|author=Ren Manetti|url=https://www.academia.edu/4428591}}</ref>\n\nDaniel Faivre calls Yahweh the most frequent vocalization, \"but considers that it is not formally consolidated\" and therefore prefers to \"use the tetragrammaton in its consonant integrity\" and then quotes the work of G. Gertoux in its French version as \"a more complete study.\"{{sfn|Faivre|2007|pp=13}}\n\nIn observations of [[4Q120]] and some Hebrew words among some scrolls, [[George Wesley Buchanan]] (Professor Emeritus at Wesley Theological Seminary) claim that \"for many years scholars have mistakenly assumed that the Tetragrammaton was to be correctly pronounced ''Y\u00e1h-weh'', treating the central vowel as if it were a consonant. This error has recently been corrected.\"{{sfn|Buchanan|2005|pp=11}} G. W. Buchanan thinks that there are arguments for the pronounciation Yahowah, but agrees with G. Gertoux in that \"based on this data, the divine name will be spelled arbitrarily ''Yehowah''.{{sfn|Buchanan|2005|pp=12}}\n\nSarah Lind reports the study of Gertoux and say that \"G. maintains a website with excerpts at divinename.net.\": G\u00e9rard Gertoux. 2002. The Name of God Y.EH.OW.AH Which is Pronounced as It is Written I_Eh_oU_Ah: Its Story. University Press of America. Translated from the French Un historique du nom divin. Un Nom Encens (L\u2019Harmattan, 1999). G. follows Maimonides\u2019 teaching that that YHWH \u201cis read as it is written,\u201d i.e., yehua, in the same way that yhwdh is vocalized yehuda\u2014applying the (coincidentally correct) Masoretic vowels. G. first considers biblical treatment of \u201cthe name\u201d: the power of the name; to know God\u2019s name; Jesus, Satan, the controversy over the name; and \u201cthe name read distinctly\u201d (reconstruction of the reading). Part 2 examines the historical record from Adam to the American Standard Version, and the name of Jesus and its connections to the name. There is a seven part appendix that includes \u201cinterpretation of the Hebrew names\u201d and \u201clack of nomina sacra in the earliest Christian papyrus.\u201d G. maintains a website with excerpts at divinename.net.\"<ref name=Lind/>\n\n==== New Testament ====\n{{main|Names and titles of God in the New Testament}}\nD. Fontaine and R. J. Wilkinson affirm that G. Gertoux is one of who have proposed that in the autograph manuscripts of some works subsequently collected to form the New Testament the Tetragrammaton or related form was found.{{sfn|Wilkinson|2015|pp=38}}{{sfn|Wilkinson|2015|pp=94}}{{sfn|Fontaine|2007|}} G. Gertoux speculated that in [[Papyrus 52]] in the place of the term 'Lord' \"the tetragram was written in full\", but in [[Papyrus 90]], \"when the ''sacred name'' was absent the word \u2018Lord\u2019 had to be written without abbreviation.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=252}}\n\n==== Some citations in bibliographies ====\nIn ''[[The Encyclopedia of Christianity]]'' by emeritus professors [[Geoffrey W. Bromiley]], emeritus professor [[Jaroslav Pelikan]], full professor [[Jan Milic Lochman]], honorary professor [[Erwin Fahlbusch]], and writer [[John Mbiti]], (published by [[Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing]] and by [[Brill Publishers|Brill]]) the work ''The name of God Y.eH.oW.aH which is pronounced as it is written I_Eh_oU_Ah: its story '' was selected as one of the ten references under the title [[Yahweh]], in which it presents among other things textual, archaeological and theological aspects, etc.{{sfn|''The Encyclopedia of Christianity''|2008|pp=823-824}}\n\nMichael Gilligan (Catholic biblical scholar) quotes G. Gertoux to affirm that \"in the world of the Bible, however, a person's name was expected to be as meaningful as possible,\"<ref name=Gilligan>{{cite web|author=Michael Gilligan|publisher=American Catholic Press|title=The Tetragrammaton in God's Word and Liturgy|url=https://www.americancatholicpress.org/Father_Gilligan_The_Tetragrammaton.html}}</ref> M. Gilligan states: \"because God is wondrous and mighty\u2014an object of awe\u2014the name of God would also be wondrous and mighty, intended to be spoken or sung with reverence. In a biblical culture, the name of God would express God\u2019s majesty and power\" and adds: \"to put it in other terms, a biblical name (in a sense) was an alter ego; it represented the person. To know someone\u2019s name was to know who and what the person was: not only his or her character or qualities, but especially his or her power, role, or function\u2014what the individual was empowered to do. To be without a name was to be worthless, of no importance.\"<ref name=Gilligan/>\n\n==== Some comments of his thesis ====\nE. J. Revell (Professor emeritus at the [[University of Toronto]]) claim: I was very interested to read the copy of your work which you sent me. Before reading your study, had no particular opinion on the pronunciation of the name of God. As a student in the 50\u2019s, I was told that scholars have determined that \u201cYahweh\u201d was the ancient pronunciation. I did not find the argument wellgrounded, but the view was held almost as an article of faith by my instructors, and I had no superior argument, so I ignored the problem. I have occasionally thought about it since, but I have not acquired any information that you have not noticed in your study. You have certainly collected more information on the question than any other study I know, and you are to be congratulated on the production of a valuable work. Many thanks for sending it to me.{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VII}}\n\n[https://fr.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henri_Cazelles H. Cazelles] (Director of the [[Institut Catholique de Paris]]): \"Thank you very much for sending me your \"In Fame only?\" a wealth of documentation. I will deposit it at the Biblical Library for the greatest benefit of the researchers ... With my congratulations and thanks.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VII}}\n\nD. C. Hopkins (Editor of the [[Near Eastern Archaeology]]): \"Thank you for submitting your rich and detailed study. Your topic is fascinating.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VII}}\n\n[[G. W. Buchanan]] (Editor of the Mellen Biblical Commentary and emeritus professor): \"Let me thank you very much for sending me your excellent thesis. I trust that will soon have it published.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VII}}\n\n[[Shlomo Morag]] (Professor at the [[Hebrew University of Jerusalem]]): \"The study is full of important evidence and gives a good survey of the research.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VII}}\n\n[[Edward Lipi\u0144ski (orientalist)|E. Lipinski]] (Professor, at the [[Katholieke Universiteit Leuven]]): \"I want to thank you for this sending and to congratulate you for the conscientious work of which this research makes proof. I'll be sure to use it if I ever come back to it.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VII-VIII}}\n\nM. Harl (Professor at the [[Universit\u00e9 de Paris IV]] Sorbonne, translator and editor of the Bible d'Alexandrie): \"Your sending fills me with admiration [...] Once again all my congratulations.\" J. Bott\u00e9ro (Director at the E.P.H.E. assyrian department): \"You seem to me both very informed and very demanding: you will get out of it and we will do a great job, which will teach me a lot! (...) You have a beautiful subject of work: I would love to see your thesis appear and read. You may be the one solving the puzzles.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VIII}}\n\n[[E. A. Livingstone]] (Doctor at the [[Oxford University]]): \"I sent your kind letter and the copy of your thesis to one of my colleagues who gave me much guidance over Old Testament material in the third edition of the Oxford Dictionary of the Christian Church (\u2026), telling me that he found your thesis most interesting; he said your case was reasonable one, and well argued.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VIII}}\n\n[[D. N. Freedman]] (Editor of the [[Anchor Bible]]): \"I was pleased to hear from you and to have your detailed treatment of this valuable and interesting subject, on which I have written from time to time. I have never been entirely atisfied with my own analysis and interpretation of the divine name in the Hebrew Bible, or with that of others, including my own teacher, [[W. F. Albright]] and his teacher (from whom Albright derived his position), [[Paul Haupt]]. At the same time, I haven\u2019t seen anything to persuade me of the superior value of another interpretation, but I will be glad to learn from your study and perhaps discover that you have finally solved this long-standing puzzle.\"{{sfn|Gertoux|2002|pp=VIII}}\n\n==== Antithesis ====\nSteven Ortlepp, in his work ''Pronunciation of the Tetragrammaton: A Historico-Linguistic Approach'' argues against his ideas.<ref>{{cite book|author=Steven Ortlepp|title=Pronunciation of the Tetragrammaton: A Historico-Linguistic Approach|year=2011|isbn=9781445272207|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=k9JEAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA25|pp=25\u201326}}</ref>\n\nEgyptologist [[John Laurence Gee]] (Research Professor of Egyptology at the Neal A. Maxwell Institute for Religious Scholarship) makes a brief review, and agrees with G. Gertoux in \"that the current consensus is unconvincing\" but on the contrary, he finds his \"arguments more passionate than persuasive\", and thus he \"also find his conclusions ultimately unconvincing.\"{{sfn|Gee|2004|}} Gertoux and Gee has been indexed in ''[[Elenchus of Biblica]]''<ref>{{cite book|author=Pontificio Istituto biblico|title=Elenchus of Biblica|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=IpfgAAAAMAAJ|publisher=Editrice Pontificio Istituto biblico|year=2004|volume=20}}\n</ref>\n\n=== Ancient World chronologies ===\nHe has proposed Assyrian and biblical chronologies,<ref name=Oxford>{{cite web|title=Oxford Postgraduate Conference in Assyriology 2015|publisher=The British Institute for the Study of Iraq|url=http://www.bisi.ac.uk/content/oxford-postgraduate-conference-assyriology-2015|accessdate=2020-03-31}}</ref><ref name=iaassyriology>{{cite web|last=Gertoux|first=G\u00e9rard|title=Scientific approach to an absolute chronology through synchronisms dated by astronomy|date=20 January 2014|location=Leiden University|publisher=IAA Assyriology|url=https://iaassyriology.com/gertoux-gerard-lyonfrance-approche-scientifique-dune-chronologie-absolue-grace-aux-synchronismes-dates-par-lastronomie-scientific-approach-absolute-chronology-synchronisms-date/}}</ref> of which, according to [[Hermann Hunger]] (Professor emeritus of Assyriology at the [[University of Vienna]]), G. Gertoux \"offers new conclusions or refutes chronologies proposed by other scholars\".<ref name=ORCID>{{cite web|url=http://orcid.org/0000-0001-5916-0445|website=ORCID|title=Gerard Gertoux}}</ref>\n\n==== Dating of Herod's death ====\n{{main|Herod the Great#Death}}\nG. Gertoux is another one who propose that [[Herod the Great]] did not die in 4 BCE, as generally accepted, but in 1 BCE.<ref name=Bioul>{{cite book|author=Bruno Bioul|title=Le recensement de Quirinius, Essai d'harmonisation des donn\u00e9es lucaniennes et jos\u00e9phiennes|pp=5|url=https://www.academia.edu/36428038}}</ref> Bruno Bioul writes that \"breaking with this consensus in the 1960s, several specialists believe that Herod would have died only in 2 or 1 BC. J.-C. See G. GERTOUX, 2015.\"<ref name=Bioul/>\n\nAccording to Giuseppe Veneziano \"the dating of [[Herod the Great|Herod]]'s death has become the center of a sometimes heated academic controversy\".{{sfn|Veneziano|2015|pp=20}} G. Veneziano describes several views by different scholars in which they propose that Herod's death was in 4 BCE or 1 BCE.{{sfn|Veneziano|2015|pp=20}} G. Veneziano continues and claims that in 1 BCE \"is supported, inter alia, by W. E. Filmer (Filmer 1966), [[A. E. Steinmann]] (Steinmann 2009), and by Gerard Gertoux (Gertoux s.d.)\", and he adds that \"however, [[Josephus]] himself, although very precise in describing the events, is a little less precise in their chronological framework and - as G. Gertoux (Gertoux 2010) recalls - provides us with at least a dozen information that contribute to making it inadequate or doubtful this date.\"{{sfn|Veneziano|2015|pp=20}} Then G. Veneziano follows to A. Steinmann and G. Gertoux: \"this and other anachronisms, widely discussed by Gertoux and by Steinmann in their writings (complete with schematics), would seem to demonstrate how the date of 1 BC it is more coherent than that which places Herod's death in 4 BC. However, without preconceptions, we now evaluate both hypotheses also from an astronomical and biblical point of view.\"{{sfn|Veneziano|2015|pp=21}}\n\n==== Dating Xerxes and Artaxerxes ====\nIn response to Gerard Gertoux, (2018). ''Dating  the  reigns  of  Xerxes  and  Artaxerxes'' in: Proceedings  of  the  61e Rencontre Assyriologique Internationale, Geneva and Bern, 22\u201326 June 2015, Peter J. Huber wrote: \"traditionally, it is assumed that Xerxes died in the year 465 BC. Recently, G\u00e9rard Gertoux (2018) has argued for a 10 years higher date. As explained in his abstract, he bases that date primarily on the Babylonian eclipse text BM 32234. Unfortunately, as I shall show in the following, a more careful scrutiny of that text does not support the higher date,\"{{sfn|Huber|2019|pp=143-147}} and that \"all eclipse observations of BM 32234 Rev. are compatible with calculations for the low chronology (death of Xerxes in 465 BCE). But at least five of them flatly contradict the calculations for Gertoux\u2019s higher chronology.\"{{sfn|Huber|2019|pp=143-147}} Gertoux reacts and publish an abstract of his work to refute Huber.{{sfn|Gertoux|2019|pp=179}}\n\n==== Carthage ====\n{{main|Carthage}}\n[[Stel Pavlou]] reports that \"Gerard Gertoux argues that recent discoveries push this date back to at least 870 BC if not further. Prior to that, the Roman poet, Silius Italicus (100-200 AD), tells us that according to legend the land there had been occupied by Pelasgians\".<ref>{{cite web|title=Carthage|date=June 6, 2010|website=Atlantipedia. An A-Z Guide To The Search For Plato's Atlantis|url=https://atlantipedia.ie/samples/tag/gerard-gertoux/|author=Stel Pavlou}}</ref>\n\n==== Lectures ====\nG. Gertoux has presented conferences at different universities:\n* \u20142011, Lecture at [[University of Edinburgh]]: ''A New Achaemenid King: Darius B, owing to Synchronized Chronology''.\n* \u20142015, Lecture at [[Oxford University]]: [https://oxfordassyriology.wordpress.com/gerard-gertoux-university-of-lyon-2/ ''Assyrian and biblical chronologies: are they reliable?''],<ref name=Oxford/>\n* \u20142015, Lecture at [[Geneva University]]: [http://rai.unibe.ch/wp-content/uploads/PDF/RAI_Programme.pdf ''Dating the Reigns of Xerxes and Artaxerxes''] which was published in 2018 in: [http://www.peeters-leuven.be/boekoverz.asp?nr=10732 Orbis Biblicus et Orientalis Series Archaeologica], 40, pp. 179-206.\n* \u20142019, Invitation at the [[Coll\u00e8ge de France]] by [[Dominique Charpin]] in order to promote his thesis [https://www.academia.edu/41022774 ''Scientific approach to an absolute chronology through synchronisms dated by astronomy''], July 11th, 2019, for the [https://rai2019.digitorient.com/en/posters/ 65th Rencontre Assyriologique Internationale \u2014 the annual conference of the International Association for Assyriology].<ref>{{cite journal|title=Text and Image: Proceedings of the 61e Rencontre Assyriologique Internationale, Geneva and Bern, 22-26 June 2015|year=2018|editor1=Attinger, Pascal|editor2=Cavigneaux, Antoine|editor3=Mittermayer, Catherine|editor4=Nov\u00e0k, Mirko|doi=10.5167/uzh-157125|location=Leuven, Belgium|publisher=Peeters Publishers|author1=S.N}}</ref>\n* \u20142019, invitation at [[American Schools of Oriental Research]], (ASOR) Annual Meeting, The Westin San Diego, San Diego, California with the subject \"Archaeology and Biblical Studies I\". Chair: [[Jonathan Rosenbaum (scholar)]]. November 20\u201323.<ref>{{cite book|title=ASOR PROGRAM GUIDE|date=November 2019|location=San Diego, California|publisher=American School of Oriental Research, 2019 Annual Meeting|isbn=978-0-89757-114-2|url=http://www.asor.org/wp-content/uploads/2019/12/2019-ASOR-Program-and-Abstract-Book.pdf}}</ref>\n\n=== Historicities ===\n==== Historicity of the Trojan War ====\n{{main|Trojan War}}\nIn the journal ''Antrocom Online Journal of Anthropology'', Xaris M. Koutelakis (awarded 2 times by the Academy of Athens and the Ministry of Culture) says that \"known archaeological data are thoroughly reexamined.\"{{sfn|Koutelakis|2007|pp=117}} He states:\n\n{{quote|On the other hand, special ceremonies had been taking place in Delos since the 12th century B.C., when, following the dispersion of the naval groups in which they had participated (that is, the Peoples of the Sea), Lycian mariners, tradesmen and pirates chose Delos as an ultimate refuge (Koutelakis, X. 2014: 96 n. 43, 44) for the safekeeping of their loot and profits, perhaps having previously destroyed Koukounaries in Paros, Grotta in Naxos, Phylakope in Melos and Hagia Eirene in Kea (Gertoux G., 2015: 37-38), and captured the inhabitants of the undefended Daskaleio-Keros or forced them to abandon their island.{{sfn|Koutelakis|2007|pp=117}}}}\n\n==== Walls of the Ruler ====\n{{main|Walls-of-the-Ruler}}\nAccording to egyptologian Jozef Hudec (Research Executive at Slovak Academy of Sciences) and Miroslav \u010cern\u00fd \"it could have contained realistic topography\" in [[story of Sinuhe]].{{sfn|Hudec|\u010cern\u00fd|2018|pp=30}} They propose that \"the Wall of the Ruler could have been assumed in Wadi Tumilat (at Tell el-Retaba, which might be the point in the defence line/wall closest to Gebel el-Ahmar), if Sinuhe could have achieved almost 90 km during one November day.\"{{sfn|Hudec|\u010cern\u00fd|2018|pp=30}} They adds: \n{{quote|The 7th day of the 3rd month of inundation (LICHTHEIM, M. Ancient Egyptian Literature. Vol. I: The Old and Middle Kingdoms, p. 223) would have been in November during the rule of [[Amenemhet I]]/[[Senwosret  I]]. (GERTOUX, G. Absolute Chronology of the Ancient World from 2840 BCE to 1533 BCE, p. 39). The length of day (between sunrise and sunset) in November is more than 10 hours, cf. Timeanddate.com, available from https://www.timeanddate.com/sun/egypt/cairo [cit. 6 January 2018]{{sfn|Hudec|\u010cern\u00fd|2018|pp=30}}}}\n\n==== Historicity of Exodus ====\n{{main|The Exodus}}\nG. Gertoux affirms the exact historicity of the [[Book of Exodus]].<ref name=Snyder/> David A. Snyder affirm that \"under the Gertoux timeline, the Hebrews would have been slaves from 1530 to 1476 BC, which is when the Exodus occurred and is enough time for God to direct Moses to tell Pharaoh to ''set my people free''.<ref name=Snyder>{{cite book|title=Abraham of Ur: A Critical Analysis of the Life and Times of the Patriarch|author=David A. Snyder|year=2015|isbn=9781491777268|url=https://books.google.com/?id=QC3fCgAAQBAJ&pg=P128}}</ref> D. A. Snyder suggest: \"the reason I give such high regard for the Gertoux timeline is the highly documented research that he uses in his ''ancient chronological system'' of study. His work equates the Hebrews with the Hyksos with some certainty.<ref name=Snyder/>\n\n=== Hebrew terms ===\n[[Ola Wikander]] (professor at Lund University) \"discuss two cases of seeming \"irregularity\" in the Tiberian [[Masoretic]] stop and fricative systems, especially concerning the relationship between those two systems \u2014and to ponder the methodological implications of this for the study of Masoretic orthography and analysis.\"{{sfn|Wikander|2019|pp=125-166}} He wrote that \"The name Ti\u00f0\u02bf\u0101l, which appears in Gen 14:1, has been plausibly explained as a borrowed Hebrew version of the Hittite royal name Tud\u1e2baliya.\"\n\n{{quote|A recent publication supporting the identification with Tud\u1e2bula (which ultimately goes back to [[Theophilus Pinches|T. G. Pinches]] in 1897) is G\u00e9rard Gertoux, Abraham and Chedorlaomer: Chronological, Historical and Archaeological Evidence (sineloco,2015), 34 (etpassim). One may note with some interest that Sayce actually suggests identifying Tud\u1e2baliya with the Tud\u1e2bula of the Spartoli tablet sin his early comment (or Tudghula, as he writes the latter), and indeed uses that purported identification as a step in arguing the connection between the Hittite name and Genesis 14!{{sfn|Wikander|2019|pp=125-166}}}}\n\n== Works ==\n* {{cite book|title=Un Historique du nom divin: Un Nom Encens|author=G\u00e9rard Gertoux|publisher=Editions L'Harmattan|date=1 August 1999|isbn=9782296391994|oclc=716841963}}\n* {{cite book|title=The Name of God Y.eH.oW.aH Which is Pronounced as it is Written I_Eh_oU_Ah. It Story|author=G\u00e9rard Gertoux|publisher=University Press of America|year=2002|isbn=9780761822042|series=G - Reference, Information and Interdisciplinary Subjects Series|oclc=59502233}}\n* {{cite book|title=Guds navns historie|author=G\u00e9rard Gertoux|publisher=K\u00f8benhavn: Gramma|year=2005|isbn=87-990125-6-1|oclc=473717946}}\n* {{cite book|title=Storia del nome di Dio. Un recente studio che f\u00e0 luce sulla corretta pronuncia del sacro nome|author=G\u00e8rard Gertoux|editor=S. Pizzorni|translator1=G. Gabrielli|translator2=M. Aragone|publisher=Azzurra 7|year=2007|isbn=9788888907093}}\n* {{cite book|title=Le nom divin dans le nouveau testament|series=Religions et Spiritualit\u00e9|author=Didier Micka\u00ebl Fontaine|publisher=Editions L'Harmattan|year=2007|isbn=9782296176096|oclc=300408308}}, (preface of G\u00e9rard Gertoux).\n* {{Cite AV media|people=Fritz Poppenberg|title=The Name of God|date=2014|publisher=Drei Linden Film}}\n* {{cite book|title=\u0418\u043c\u044f \u0411\u043e\u0433\u0430: \u0435\u0433\u043e \u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0440\u0438\u044f \u0438 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0438\u0437\u043d\u043e\u0448\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0435|author=\u0416\u0435\u0440\u0430\u0440 \u0416\u0435\u0440\u0442\u043e|location=Kiev|publisher=Strelbytskyy Multimedia Publishing|date=2 February 2018|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=EBtKDwAAQBAJ}}\n* {{cite book|title=Text and image: proceedings of the 61e Rencontre Assyriologique Internationale, Geneva and Bern, 22-26 June 2015|editor=Pascal Attinger|author=G\u00e9rard Gertoux|editor2=Attinger P.|editor3=Cavigneaux A.|editor4=Mittermayer C.|editor5=Novak M.|publisher=Leuven; Bristol, CT: Peeters Publishers|year=2018|series=Orbis biblicus et orientalis., Series Archaeologica|volume=Vol. 40|isbn=978-90-429-3713-0|oclc=1046070112}}\n\nSome other selfpublished works are found in [[Semantic Scholar]]'s web page and [[ORCID]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Gerard Gertoux|website=Semantic Scholar|url=https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/Gerard-Gertoux/108067232}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n*{{cite book|title=Les t\u00e9moins de Jehovah: Pour un christianisme original|series=Religion et sciences humaines|first=Philippe|last=Barbey|publisher=[[Editions L'Harmattan]]|year=2003|isbn=9782296315914|pp=19|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-W9Ul5pFIOQC&pg=PA19|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=La caricatura e il sacro: Islam, ebraismo e cristianisimo a confronto|series=Transizioni (Vita e pensiero (Firm)|volume=Vol. 21|first=Fran\u00e7ois|last=Boespflug|publisher=Vita e Pensiero|year=2007|isbn=9788834313824|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=98H0BCqPhcAC&pg=PA74|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=Yahweh|work=The Encyclodedia of Christianity|volume=Vol 5|series=The Encyclopedia of Christianity|editor1=[[Geoffrey William Bromiley|Bromiley, Geoffrey William]]|editor2=[[Erwin Fahlbusch]]|editor3=[[Jan Milic Lochman]]|editor4=[[John Mbiti]]|editor5=[[Jaroslav Pelikan]]|translator=Geoffrey William Bromiley|editor6=[[Jaroslav Pelikan]]|publisher=Wm. B. Eerdmans Publishing|year=2008|isbn=9780802824172|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lZUBZlth2qgC&pg=PA823|pp=823\u2013824|ref={{harvid|The Encyclopedia of Christianity|2008}}}}\n*{{cite book|title=The Book of Daniel|first=George Wesley|last=Buchanan|series=Mellen Biblical Commentary: Old Testament|volume=Vol. 25|publisher=Wipf and Stock Publishers|year=2005|isbn=9781592440214|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5NFKAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA12|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|title=Mythes de la Gen\u00e8se, gen\u00e8se des mythes|series=Religions et Spiritualit\u00e9|first=Daniel|last=Faivre|publisher=Editions L'Harmattan|year=2007|isbn=9782296174580|pp=1